@node Overview
@chapter Overview

@samp{ai-agent.el} collects the Emacs integration layer for AI coding command-line tools. It provides a shared session model, a unified transient menu, notification handling, terminal helpers, and backend modules for Claude Code and Codex.

The package is split into a small core and backend modules. The core file, @samp{ai-agent.el}, is backend-agnostic: it knows how to register AI tools, find their buffers, dispatch shared commands, render backend icons, assign stable session keys, and present a single menu. @samp{ai-agent-claude.el} integrates @samp{claude-code.el} with Claude-specific account switching, status polling, usage polling, branch navigation, batch TODO processing, and hook setup. @samp{ai-agent-codex.el} integrates @samp{codex.el} with Codex-specific theme sync, skill execution, handoff, auditing, debugging, and modeline helpers.

The main workflow is to load @samp{ai-agent.el}, then require the backend modules you use. Once the Claude and Codex modules are loaded, @samp{M-x ai-agent-menu} and @samp{M-x ai-agent-start-or-switch} operate across both tools. Sessions are grouped by account when the backend exposes account metadata, highlighted when waiting for input, and disambiguated by project and instance name when several sessions share a directory.

The package depends on @samp{transient} for menus and @samp{consult} for completion. The Claude backend expects @samp{claude-code.el}. The Codex backend expects @samp{codex.el}. Optional integrations use packages such as @samp{yasnippet}, @samp{doom-modeline}, @samp{gptel}, @samp{agent-log}, and @samp{monet} when those are available.

